        <briefdescription>
<para>Helper method to compute the coordinates of a hole in the (α,β) plane corresponding to a mukai vector. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Suppose (r, lH, s) is the mukai vector of a spherical vector bundle on a degree d K3 surface (H^2 = 2d). Then </para>
<sect1 id="classsrc_1_1_projective_c_y_1_1_k3_geometric_chamber_1autotoc_md2">
<title>dl^2 - rs = -1. For a corresponding hole in the (α,β) plane, we must have the real and imaginary part of</title></sect1>
<sect1 id="classsrc_1_1_projective_c_y_1_1_k3_geometric_chamber_1autotoc_md3">
<title>&lt; exp(αΗ + ι βΗ) , (r, lH, s) &gt; vanish. This gives</title><para>0 = &lt;(1, αH, (α^2 - β^2)d), (r, lH, s)&gt; = 2dal - s - rd(α^2 - β^2) 0 = &lt;(0, βΗ, 2αβd), (r, lH, s)&gt; = 2βdl - 2rdαβ = 2dβ(l - rα)</para>
<para>The second equation gives β = 0 or l = rα. Since βΗ is necessarily ample, we must have β &gt; 0. Therefore, l = rα. Substituting into the first equation simplifies to</para>
<para>dl^2 - rs + dr^2 β^2 = 0</para>
<para>Using dl^2 - rs = -1, we find that β = 1/r√d.</para>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>int</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>r The first component of the mukai vector </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>int</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>l The second component of the mukai vector </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>int</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>s The third component of the mukai vector</para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>tuple The coordinates of the hole in the (α,β) plane </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
</sect1>
